2.4   Nerve Fibres Running to and from the Diaphragm

Because the diaphragm is striated muscle, it is controlled by somatic motor neurons, as are the skeletal muscles of the limbs and body wall.  
The cell bodies of these somatic motor neurons are located in the C3 - C5 segments of the spinal cord and their axons form the phrenic nerve. 
Sensory fibres return from the diaphragm and its overlying pleura, as well as from the mediastinal parietal pleura and the pericardial sac, to the C3-C5 segments of the spinal cord.  
The phrenic nerve also contains sympathetic postganglionic fibres arising from cervical sympathetic chain ganglia, destined to control vascular smooth muscle within its territory.
